{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17102"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17102"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.73,0.04,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77859"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17102"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5122"},{"type":"tags","id":"5128"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26658"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77859"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with gradual enlargement of her hands, feet, and facial features over several years. She also reports increased sweating, joint pain, and fatigue (Image). These symptoms are characteristic of acromegaly, a condition of excess growth hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of growth hormone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct stimulation of bone growth plates","Stimulation of insulin-like growth factor 1 production","Inhibition of growth hormone-releasing hormone","Direct promotion of muscle protein synthesis","Stimulation of thyroid hormone production"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone primarily acts by stimulating the production of \u003Cstrong\u003Einsulin-like growth factor 1\u003C/strong\u003E from the liver. This mediator then promotes growth in multiple target tissues including bone, muscle, and other organs. In acromegaly, excess growth hormone leads to elevated insulin-like growth factor 1, resulting in characteristic soft tissue and bone overgrowth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of bone growth plates\u003C/strong\u003E: growth hormone\u0027s effects on bone occur primarily through insulin-like growth factor 1 rather than through direct action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect promotion of muscle protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: while growth hormone has some direct effects on protein metabolism, its major growth-promoting effects occur through insulin-like growth factor 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of growth hormone-releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E: although growth hormone provides negative feedback, this is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of thyroid hormone production\u003C/strong\u003E: growth hormone does not directly regulate thyroid hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone has additional metabolic effects including increased protein synthesis, enhanced lipolysis, and reduced insulin sensitivity. In acromegaly, these effects can lead to complications such as diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Growth hormone (somatropin) stimulates production of insulin-like growth factor 1 from the liver to promote growth.","Growth hormone has important metabolic effects including increased protein synthesis, lipolysis, and insulin resistance.","Excess growth hormone in adults causes acromegaly, characterised by enlargement of hands, feet, and facial features."],"references":["Ershadinia N, Tritos NA. Diagnosis and Treatment of Acromegaly: An Update. Mayo Clin Proc. 2022;97(2):333-346. doi:10.1016/j.mayocp.2021.11.007","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17102"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21445"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21445"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/954dXasoqHUvmoFgN7XNjLODLHNFKj.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/954dXasoqHUvmoFgN7XNjLODLHNFKj.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":292,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T17:57:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T17:58:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77859"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}